  "plan_analysis": "The meta-question hinges on how the Metaculus community forecast for \u201cArtemis II will succeed before 2027\u201d moves in the final eight days before 2026-03-13.  Two broad evidence streams matter:\n\nA. Technical / program news: Any fresh information on Artemis II hardware readiness (Orion heat-shield work, SLS upper-stage helium flow fix, pad processing, flight-readiness reviews, congressional funding signals, crew training milestones) could quickly nudge confidence up or down.\n\nB. Forecast-behaviour statistics: How volatile is a Metaculus community prediction this close to the snapshot time?  What is the historical frequency of \u22651 pp moves within a week for space-mission questions or in general?  Understanding this base-rate plus trend direction (75 % now, 76 % a few days ago) helps estimate the probability of crossing the 76 % line.\n\nThe pre-research bundle already includes the current 75 % value, the full long-run history, and background on past schedule slips but nothing about:\n \u2022 very recent (last few days) Artemis II engineering / managerial updates\n \u2022 whether a key review, test, or congressional hearing is scheduled before 13 March\n \u2022 quantitative data on typical Metaculus forecast drift in the final week\n \u2022 historical success / delay rates for comparable NASA crewed missions to calibrate community bias\n \u2022 any contrarian negative developments (budget cuts, further hardware issues) since the latest scrape\n\nThe search strategy therefore splits: 1-5 target freshest news and scheduled events that could plausibly shift the forecast; 6-8 pull historical/analytical pieces on Metaculus volatility and mission precedents to anchor base-rate reasoning.",
